Moving into the actual, choices for tables abound. Nightstands are the standards here, however, you may use a console table or accent table to keep all of your makeup or display family photos - adding a little bit of personality towards the room. If you want, you can include a console or sofa table to the end from the bed, giving you a location to put a set screen TV. There's no rule saying it has to be halfway over the room.

This is the great thing about all the tables in your house. They fill so many roles, from offering you a convenient place to keep the keys within the entryway to using a table in front of the sofa to help you kick up the feet and relax a bit following a long day at the office.

In the kitchen area, you can add a pleasant kitchen table to offset or enhance you cabinet hardware and decor. One of the most popular options nowadays is to opt for a bench or corner unit that makes better utilization of your sq footage, adding lots of seating in a very little space. If you have room in the center of your home or after it, you may want to go with a more traditional kitchen table or maybe even a bistro table flanked by a few bistro chairs or stools. Another great choice is to choose a table which has folding sides so you can make the table bigger when guests are gone and reduce its footprint when no one is using it.

Finally, don't overlook some specialty tables in your house. These include nesting tables, which can either replace the coffee table or an end table. The 2 or three tables don't take up much space before you need additional tables for a party or holiday. Then your magic happens, a single table quickly becomes 2 or 3, allowing you to add tables through the room so visitors have a convenient spot to set their drinks and plates throughout a party.